    "body": "The idea is also discussed on [ML](http://lists.numenta.org/pipermail/nupic-hackers_lists.numenta.org/2014-April/000592.html)\r\n\r\nWhether NuPIC should use more the modular/OOP approach - splitting logic to stand-alone classes, using inheritance, .. , compared to the current situation with larger, single-file implementations and alternatives in \"copy-n-modify\"-ed files. \r\n\r\nWe are talking about `SP` currently, `TP` would fall in that category too. \r\n\r\nI will try to list the pros and cons from the ML discussion (well, I'm biased, so feel free to jump in with opinion! :) )\r\n\r\n`OOP` is: \r\n- easy to read (not so long files, all functions/variables are related to the logic) \r\n- easier to cooperate (long time) (my alt. boosting impl. can still benefit from changes in SP made by someone else)\r\n- forces \"nicer coding\"/API (\"parts\" communicate by public methods only, no direct access to variables where it should not be. Makes alt impl much easier)\r\n\r\n`single file` is:\r\n- easy to read (no inheritance, abstract classes, all in one file..)\r\n- easier to develop alternatives (short time) (just copy files, make changes..)\r\n\r\nBoth allow the `goal` of \"single best algorithm\" that is used as default.  \r\n\r\nRelated:\r\n- [ ] standalone Boosting/Inhibition https://github.com/numenta/nupic/issues/824\r\n- [ ] SP/TP/TM extend from (abstract) Layer class https://github.com/numenta/nupic/issues/1860\r\n- [ ] Column class https://github.com/numenta/nupic/issues/1861",
    "repo": "numenta/nupic"
